onstructs a vision of translation uniquely attuned to the place of Brazil in the Americas. Brune reveals the hemispheric underpinnings of works by renowned Brazilian writers such as Machado de Assis, Sousândrade, Mário de Andrade, Silviano Santiago, and Adriana Lisboa. In the process, she rethinks the dynamics between cosmopolitan and national desires and between center and periphery in global literary markets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBrazilian literaturexTranslationsxHistory and criticism. 0aBrazilian prose literaturexTranslationsxHistory and criticism. 0aPortuguese literaturexTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aTranslating and interpretingzBrazil. 0aTravel in literature. 0aTravelers' writings, BrazilianxHistory and criticism. 0aTravelers' writings, BrazilianzAmericaxHistory and criticism. 0aTravelers' writings, BrazilianzUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Translation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848063340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438480633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438480633/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles